You are developing an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.
This is a solo developer project until production deployment.

All git operations must follow these conventions strictly.

==============================
BRANCHING STRATEGY
==============================

This project uses a simplified Feature Branch model (solo developer):

main          — single source of truth, always stable and working
feature/*     — new feature development (one branch per feature)
fix/*         — bug fixes

Branch lifecycle:
1. Create feature branch from main.
2. Develop on feature branch with granular commits.
3. Verify and test on feature branch.
4. Merge feature branch into main.
5. Delete the feature branch.

There is NO develop branch. There is NO PR process.
main receives direct merges from completed feature branches.

==============================
BRANCH NAMING
==============================

Format: type/F{number}-short-description

Examples:
  feature/F1-monorepo-setup
  feature/F6-auth-module
  feature/F14-design-system
  feature/F18-fair-list-page
  fix/F10-customer-search-bug

Rules:
- Use lowercase and hyphens only.
- Always include the feature number from docs/phase-1-features.md.
- Keep descriptions short (2-4 words).
- Never use spaces or special characters.

==============================
FEATURE BRANCH WORKFLOW
==============================

Starting a feature:
  git checkout main
  git checkout -b feature/F{n}-short-description

During development (granular commits on feature branch):
  git add .
  git commit -m "feat(api): add Fair model to Prisma schema"
  git commit -m "chore(prisma): run migration for fair model"
  git commit -m "feat(api): implement FairService with CRUD methods"

Completing a feature (after all tests pass):
  git checkout main
  git merge feature/F{n}-short-description
  git branch -d feature/F{n}-short-description

==============================
WHEN TO COMMIT
==============================

Commit after each meaningful step within a feature:

- Shared package types/schemas defined → commit
- Prisma schema updated → commit
- Migration executed → commit
- Service layer implemented → commit
- Controller layer implemented → commit
- Frontend component created → commit
- Tests written and passing → commit

Each commit should leave the codebase in a working state.
Never commit broken code — stash or fix before committing.

==============================
WHEN TO MERGE TO MAIN
==============================

Merge to main ONLY when ALL of the following are true:

- All feature sub-items from phase-1-features.md are implemented.
- No TypeScript errors across all apps.
- No lint errors.
- All tests pass.
- Feature works end-to-end (if applicable).

Never merge incomplete or broken features to main.

==============================
DIRECT COMMITS TO MAIN (EXCEPTIONS)
==============================

Small non-code changes may be committed directly to main without a branch:

- Documentation updates (docs: update phase-1-features status)
- Typo fixes (docs: fix typo in tech-stack)
- README updates

All code changes MUST go through a feature branch.

==============================
COMMIT MESSAGE FORMAT
==============================

This project follows Conventional Commits specification.

Format: type(scope): description

Types:
  feat     — new feature or functionality
  fix      — bug fix
  refactor — code restructuring without behavior change
  style    — formatting, whitespace, missing semicolons (no logic change)
  docs     — documentation changes
  test     — adding or updating tests
  chore    — build, config, dependency updates, tooling
  perf     — performance improvement

Scopes (match monorepo apps):
  api      — backend (NestJS)
  web      — frontend (Next.js)
  shared   — packages/shared
  prisma   — database schema and migrations
  config   — project-wide configuration
  docs     — documentation files

Examples:
  feat(api): add fair CRUD endpoints
  feat(web): implement fair list page with card grid
  feat(shared): add Zod validation schemas for customer
  fix(api): handle cascade delete on fair removal
  refactor(web): extract FairCard into separate component
  chore(config): configure ESLint and Prettier
  test(api): add unit tests for FairService
  docs: update phase-1-features status

Rules:
- Use imperative mood: "add" not "added" or "adds".
- First line max 72 characters.
- Lowercase after the colon (no capital letter).
- No period at the end of the subject line.
- Reference feature number in body when relevant.

Multi-line commit (for complex changes):
  feat(api): add customer management module

  Implements CRUD operations for customers within fairs.
  Includes search by name/company and conversion rate filter.

  Ref: Feature #10

==============================
COMMIT GRANULARITY
==============================

- One logical change per commit — do not bundle unrelated changes.
- Prefer smaller, focused commits over large monolithic ones.
- Database migrations get their own dedicated commit.
- Configuration changes get their own commit.

Good (4 focused commits on feature branch):
  feat(api): add Fair model to Prisma schema
  chore(prisma): run migration for fair model
  feat(api): implement FairService with CRUD methods
  feat(api): add FairController with endpoints

Bad (1 monolithic commit):
  feat: add fair module with schema, service, controller, and tests

==============================
TAGGING & RELEASES
==============================

When Phase 1 is complete and ready for production:
  git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "Phase 1: Fuar CRM Web Application"
  git push origin v1.0.0

Use semantic versioning: v{major}.{minor}.{patch}

==============================
.GITIGNORE RULES
==============================

Must ignore:
- node_modules/ (all levels)
- .env (all levels, never commit secrets)
- dist/ and build/ directories
- .next/ (Next.js build cache)
- prisma/*.db (SQLite dev databases if any)
- coverage/ (test coverage reports)
- .DS_Store (macOS)
- *.log files

Must track:
- .env.example (with keys, no values)
- prisma/schema.prisma
- prisma/migrations/ (all migration files)
- lock files (package-lock.json)

==============================
IMPORTANT
==============================

- Never commit secrets, credentials, or API keys.
- Never force push to main.
- Never commit directly to main (except small doc changes).
- Always test before merging to main.
- When a second developer joins, introduce develop branch and PR process.
